<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="153" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,990,2023]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1026,1051]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Description</emphasis>
. Massive sponge, consisting of a set of interconnected lobes, each provided with an apical oscule (
<figureCitation box="[159,240,1062,1087]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 13. Sponges in situ A. Erylus formosus. B. Cliona amplicavata excavating on Lobatus gigas shell. C. Cliona flavifodina. D. Chondrilla caribensis, E. Hymeniacidon caerulea." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238828/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,240,1063,1087]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Body measures 
<quantity box="[465,520,1062,1087]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" unit="cm" value="6.0">6 cm</quantity>
in height by 
<quantity box="[671,748,1062,1087]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" unit="cm" value="3.5">3.5 cm</quantity>
in width. Oscules 
<quantity box="[960,1075,1062,1087]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" unit="mm" value="3.25" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.5">2.5–4 mm</quantity>
in diameter, tending to collapse once out of the water. The body wall has homogeneously distributed ostia. The sponge surface is smooth underwater but wrinkled once out of the water. The consistency is firm, slightly compressible. Its color 
<emphasis box="[1332,1409,1135,1158]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">in vivo</emphasis>
is dark brown outside, light brown inside, all dark brown in alcohol.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,990,2023]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,1206,1231]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Skeleton</emphasis>
. Cortex consist of two layers, about 
<number box="[767,809,1207,1231]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="200.0">200</number>
µm thick, the outer one, ectochrote with abundant microstrongyles tangentially placed, and below a thicker layer with aspidasters packed together. The choanosomal skeleton is radially oriented near the surface, becoming strewn in confusion at the centre (
<figureCitation box="[1267,1342,1278,1303]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1196,1218]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Erylus formosus Sollas, 1886: A. Cross section of skeletal arrangement showing the cortex and radial arrangement of megascleres. B. Aspidasters and centrotylote microstrongyles in LM. C. Oxeas and aspidasters. D. Aspidaster and centrotylotes microstrongyles in SEM." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238817/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
Fig. 
<number box="[1327,1342,1279,1303]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A). The orthotriaene rhabds are perpendicular to the surface, with cladomes supporting the cortex, and several bundles of oxeas 
<number box="[227,311,1350,1375]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="75.0" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="50.0">50–100</number>
µm in diameter, some single oxeas traversing the cortex. Tylasters, oxyasters and centrotylote microstrongyles are scattered in the choanosome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,990,2023]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1422,1447]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Spicules</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[315,394,1422,1447]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1196,1218]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Erylus formosus Sollas, 1886: A. Cross section of skeletal arrangement showing the cortex and radial arrangement of megascleres. B. Aspidasters and centrotylote microstrongyles in LM. C. Oxeas and aspidasters. D. Aspidaster and centrotylotes microstrongyles in SEM." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238817/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
Figs. 
<number box="[380,394,1423,1447]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B–D). Megascleres are fusiform oxeas, slightly curved to styloid, 
<number box="[1157,1255,1422,1447]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="750.0" valueMax="900.0" valueMin="600.0">600–900</number>
× 
<number box="[1290,1381,1423,1447]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="15.1" valueMax="18.2" valueMin="12.0">12–18.2</number>
µm, orthotriaenes with rhabdomes 
<number box="[500,599,1458,1483]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="467.5" valueMax="550.0" valueMin="385.0">385–550</number>
× 
<number box="[634,683,1459,1483]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="18.2">18.2</number>
µm in length, with clads around 
<number box="[1076,1118,1459,1483]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="143.0">143</number>
× 
<number box="[1154,1182,1459,1483]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="13.0">13</number>
µm. Microscleres are aspidasters, 
<number box="[287,406,1494,1519]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="181.6" valueMax="213.2" valueMin="150.0">150–213.2</number>
µm long, centrotylotes microstrongyles for the most part with some centrotylote microxeas, 
<number box="[151,221,1530,1555]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="42.0" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="39.0">39–45</number>
× 
<number box="[251,309,1530,1555]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="4.35" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="2.7">2.7-6</number>
µm (
<figureCitation box="[369,436,1530,1555]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1196,1218]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Erylus formosus Sollas, 1886: A. Cross section of skeletal arrangement showing the cortex and radial arrangement of megascleres. B. Aspidasters and centrotylote microstrongyles in LM. C. Oxeas and aspidasters. D. Aspidaster and centrotylotes microstrongyles in SEM." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238817/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
Fig. 
<number box="[421,436,1531,1555]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
D), tylasters 
<number box="[579,671,1530,1555]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="14.75" valueMax="16.5" valueMin="13.0">13–16.5</number>
µm in diameter and oxyasters, 
<number box="[1023,1094,1531,1555]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="15.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="12.0">12–18</number>
µm in diameter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="153" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,990,2023]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,491,1566,1591]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
. The current is the first record of 
<taxonomicName box="[869,1052,1566,1591]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[869,1052,1566,1591]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Erylus formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[1227,1316,1566,1591]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. However, it is well represented in the Caribbean Sea, from the north coast of Quintana Roo (
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez" box="[1098,1354,1603,1627]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" refString="Gomez, P. &amp; Green, G. (1984) Sistematica de las esponjas marinas de Puerto Morelos, Quintana Roo, Mexico. Anales del Instituto de Ciencias del Mar y Limnologia de la Universidad Nacional Autonoma de Mexico, 11, 69 - 90." type="journal article" year="1984">
Gómez &amp; Green 
<number box="[1297,1354,1603,1627]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) to the south of 
<collectingCountry box="[253,342,1639,1662]" name="Panama" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Panama</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Diaz" box="[359,482,1638,1663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" refString="Diaz, M. C. (2005) Common sponges from shallow marine habitats from Bocas del Toro Region, Panama. Caribbean Journal of Science, 41, 465 - 475." type="journal article" year="2005">
Díaz 
<number box="[422,482,1638,1663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), Carrie Bow Cay, 
<collectingCountry box="[704,776,1638,1663]" name="Belize" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Belize</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler" box="[793,1005,1638,1663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" refString="Rutzler, K., Piatoni, C., Soest van, R. W. M. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2014) Diversity of sponges (Porifera) from cryptic habitats on the Belize barrier reef near Carrie Bow Cay. Zootaxa, 3805, 1 - 129. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3805.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Rützler 
<emphasis box="[886,938,1638,1663]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">et al</emphasis>
<number box="[947,1005,1639,1663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and the coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[1213,1281,1638,1663]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hajdu" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" refString="Hajdu, E., Peixinho, S. &amp; Fernandez, C. C. (2011) Esponjas marinhas da Bahia: guia de campo e laboratorio. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro, 246 pp." type="book" year="2011">
Hajdu 
<emphasis box="[1377,1436,1638,1663]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[151,211,1675,1699]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It has even been recorded in eastern Florida, near Bimini 
<collectingCountry box="[866,937,1674,1699]" name="Iceland" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Island</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[948,1054,1674,1699]" name="Bahamas" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Bahamas</collectingCountry>
, at 
<quantity box="[1091,1196,1674,1699]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.65" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="0.3" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" unit="m" value="26.5" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="3.0">3 to 50 m</quantity>
depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Wiedenmayer" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" refString="Wiedenmayer, F. (1977) Shallow water sponges of the Western Bahamas. Experientia Supplementum, 28, 1 - 287. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 3 - 0348 - 5797 - 0" type="journal article" year="1977">
Wiedenmayer 
<number box="[151,211,1711,1735]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="1977.0">1977</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="153" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,990,2023]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1746,1771]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[324,510,1746,1771]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[324,510,1746,1771]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Erylus formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[727,889,1746,1771]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="trisphaerus">
<emphasis box="[727,889,1746,1771]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. trisphaerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(de 
<bibRefCitation author="Laubenfels" box="[943,1135,1746,1771]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" refString="Laubenfels, M. W. de (1953) Sponges from the Gulf of Mexico. Bulletin of Marine Science Gulf and Caribbean, 2, 511 - 557." type="journal article" year="1953">
Laubenfels 
<number box="[1078,1135,1746,1771]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="1953.0">1953</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) (see below). However, it differs as its body lobes are close together, resulting in a massive complex of lobes, whereas the lobes in 
<taxonomicName class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="trisphaerus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. trisphaerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are well separated from each other. The color is brown alive in both species, but in 
<taxonomicName box="[1248,1384,1819,1843]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[1248,1384,1819,1843]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is homogeneous throughout the whole body, whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[761,921,1854,1879]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="trisphaerus">
<emphasis box="[761,921,1854,1879]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. trisphaerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is blackish on top and light brown to beige towards the base of the sponge. The skeletal elements show the most important differences between these species, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,285,1927,1951]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[151,285,1927,1951]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[434,594,1926,1951]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="trisphaerus">
<emphasis box="[434,594,1926,1951]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. trisphaerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by aspidasters that are not trilobulate such as in 
<taxonomicName box="[1142,1300,1926,1951]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="trisphaerus">
<emphasis box="[1142,1300,1926,1951]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. trisphaerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1317,1383,1926,1951]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1368,1390]" captionTargetBox="[340,1246,193,1345]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[340,1247,193,1346]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Spicule composition in Erylus trisphaerus (de Laubenfels, 1953): A. Trilobate aspidasters at different stages of development, (from left, mature, to right, early). B. Hilum detail of aspidaster. C. Chiasters I with microspined rays. D. Chiasters II, smaller and lightly microspined. E. Oxyasters, minutely spined." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238819/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
Fig. 
<number box="[1369,1383,1927,1951]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A) it is simply elongated (
<figureCitation box="[400,473,1962,1987]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1196,1218]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1172]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Erylus formosus Sollas, 1886: A. Cross section of skeletal arrangement showing the cortex and radial arrangement of megascleres. B. Aspidasters and centrotylote microstrongyles in LM. C. Oxeas and aspidasters. D. Aspidaster and centrotylotes microstrongyles in SEM." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238817/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
Fig. 
<number box="[458,473,1963,1987]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
D). It mainly has microstrongyles instead of microxeas, and spicular meristics of megascleres differ on the average, are thinner and smaller in 
<taxonomicName box="[834,993,1998,2023]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Erylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="trisphaerus">
<emphasis box="[834,993,1998,2023]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">E. trisphaerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
